						<div class="postbody">I think I understand now Tepples. 139 decoders work on SNES because the hardware can address more than the 4MB address range. This wont work on a Genesis because there is nothing to signal to the 139 that it needs an address over the 4MB threshold, is that correct? If this is correct then what signals to the mapper to use an address over $FFFFFF?<br /><br />Edit: Well that doesn't seem right actually, after reading a wiki about Snes memory mapping for Hi and Lo roms it only supports up to 32mb according to what this says. So how is it that a 139 decoder works for a snes game that is 48mb like Chrimson Echos for example? How does OE on the MAD-1 and A19 on the rom signal to the 139 to use and address over 4MB?<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Super_NES_Programming/SNES_memory_map">http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Super_NES_ ... memory_map</a><!-- m --></div>

